    1	# Elliott-Halberstam Conjecture & Gap Structure Experiments
    2	
    3	**Task #4, Experiments 3 & 4**
    4	**Date:** 2026-04-05
    5	
    6	## Experiment 3: Elliott-Halberstam Conjecture and Counting
    7	
    8	### Setup
    9	- Tested primorial moduli q = 6, 30, 210
    10	- For each q, computed pi(x; q, a) for all coprime residues a
    11	- Summed to reconstruct pi(x) and compared with li(x)/phi(q) approximation
    12	- Tested x = 10^3, 10^4, 10^5, 10^6
    13	
    14	### Results
    15	
    16	**Reconstruction is exact (tautology):** Summing pi(x;q,a) over all coprime residues + primes dividing q always gives pi(x) exactly. This is just partitioning primes by residue class -- no information gained.
    17	
    18	**Error cancellation in the approximation:**
    19	
    20	| q | x | sum of errors (li/phi approx) | RMS per-class error | cancellation ratio |
    21	|---|---|---:|---:|---:|
    22	| 6 | 10^3 | -11.6 | 6.5 | 0.89 |
    23	| 6 | 10^6 | -131.6 | 67.9 | 0.97 |
    24	| 30 | 10^3 | -12.6 | 2.5 | 0.63 |
    25	| 30 | 10^6 | -132.6 | 21.8 | 0.76 |
    26	| 210 | 10^3 | -13.6 | 1.0 | 0.30 |
    27	| 210 | 10^6 | -133.6 | 13.2 | 0.21 |
    28	
    29	The cancellation ratio = |sum of errors| / (phi(q) * RMS). Lower means MORE cancellation. With larger q (210), individual errors are smaller but they do NOT cancel well enough -- the sum of errors converges to li(x) - pi(x), which is the same error as using li(x) directly.
